for choosing this one.

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:32.430
TODD WOMACK: You chose wisely.

00:00:32.430 --> 00:00:33.180
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:34.870
TODD WOMACK: You actually
played a Google employee.

00:00:34.870 --> 00:00:36.150
BJ NOVAK: What if this is
a trick, and everyone who

00:00:36.150 --> 00:00:37.066
came to this is fired?

00:00:39.930 --> 00:00:41.610
Be a great prank.

00:00:41.610 --> 00:00:44.140
TODD WOMACK: For you.

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:45.685
So what've you got going on?

00:00:45.685 --> 00:00:47.560
What are you doing in
New York, first of all.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:51.602
BJ NOVAK: I came here to
visit the company Google.

00:00:51.602 --> 00:00:53.060
TODD WOMACK: Massive
search engine.

00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:54.120
BJ NOVAK: Massive search engine.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:55.920
I don't know if you know,
I played a Google employee

00:00:55.920 --> 00:00:56.470
in a movie.

00:00:56.470 --> 00:00:58.011
TODD WOMACK: I was
about to say that.

00:00:58.011 --> 00:00:59.610
Did you do any research?

00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:00.710
BJ NOVAK: Yes, for years.

00:01:00.710 --> 00:01:03.700
I used the search engine.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:05.720
I used the email, the maps.

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:07.880
I got very deep into
it, so I could really

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:09.640
understand the
mindset of someone

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:13.086
for whom Google is an
essential part of their life.

00:01:13.086 --> 00:01:14.210
TODD WOMACK: See, he cares.

00:01:14.210 --> 00:01:16.340
He did the research,
did the work.

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:18.700
So tell us about the book.

00:01:18.700 --> 00:01:21.020
BJ NOVAK: Well, this
book-- the reason I'm here

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:24.100
in general in New York this
week is for the paperback launch

00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:27.090
of this book, "One More Thing--
Stories and Other Stories,"

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:30.400
which is a collection of
64 short stories of very

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:33.850
different lengths, and
topics, and sometimes tones,

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:37.540
and always themes
that really are meant

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:42.180
to be, in my opinion, a book
of fiction for the social media

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:43.380
age, in a way.

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:47.060
This is for a generation
that I include myself

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:52.880
in where we can click around,
and flip around, and find

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:55.850
different things that we're
in the mood for at any moment.

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:58.160
And I wanted a book
that felt like that too,

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:01.450
that you could flip through
it and visually see,

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:02.290
this looks short.

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:03.660
This looks sweet.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:05.130
This looks involving.

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:06.330
This looks crazy.

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:08.110
This has a lot of swears in it.

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:10.810
This one is more innocent.

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:14.630
My mind was working in
a very jagged way when

00:02:14.630 --> 00:02:16.620
I was-- I had just
left the office,

00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:19.220
and my mind was flooded
with all these ideas.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:22.660
And I thought it would be
great if I could pull it off,

00:02:22.660 --> 00:02:25.300
to write a jagged book.

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:28.690
So they're all
comedic, but they're

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:32.187
expressive of different
feelings and moods, as well

00:02:32.187 --> 00:02:33.020
as different topics.

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:33.280
TODD WOMACK: Right.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:35.370
Yeah, there's some that
are just sweet and sad.

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:37.680
And they're all pretty
funny, the ones that I read.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.305
I didn't have time to read
the whole book since Monday,

00:02:40.305 --> 00:02:41.180
since I got the book.

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:44.080
But I'm going to read a couple
of these titles of the stories

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:47.370
in here, just because the titles
themselves are pretty funny.

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:49.410
"'The Something,'
by John Grisham."

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:51.194
I thought that was pretty good.

00:02:51.194 --> 00:02:52.860
BJ NOVAK: That's a
story in which author

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:56.600
John Grisham wakes up and sees
a full-page ad in "The New York

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:59.500
Times" congratulating him from
his publisher, Random House,

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.400
on his book called,
"The Something."

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:02.900
And it turns out,
he had just mailed

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.602
in a manuscript with that
as a placeholder title.

00:03:05.602 --> 00:03:07.990
And they had never checked it.

00:03:07.990 --> 00:03:11.220
And it becomes a meditation
on perfectionism.

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:12.220
The book's number one.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:13.170
Everyone loves it.

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:15.230
They think "The Something"
is a cool title.

00:03:15.230 --> 00:03:18.904
And does he let it go, or do
heads roll at Random House?

00:03:18.904 --> 00:03:20.070
Yeah, you tell me the title.

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:20.630
I'll tell you what it's about.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:21.870
TODD WOMACK: His follow
up is "Working Title."

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:22.922
Right.

00:03:22.922 --> 00:03:26.970
Here we go. "The Man Who Posted
Pictures of Everything He Ate."

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:27.720
That's quite good.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:29.400
BJ NOVAK: That's so short,
I could even read it later

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:29.820
if you want.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:30.520
That's one of those--

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:31.020
TODD WOMACK: That's
what I was going to say,

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:31.810
if you want to do a
little bit of that.

00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:32.560
BJ NOVAK: Perfect for this room.

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:32.920
Yeah.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:33.500
TODD WOMACK: All right.

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:34.860
Would you guys like
to hear that later?

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:35.485
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:03:35.485 --> 00:03:36.443
TODD WOMACK: All right.

00:03:36.443 --> 00:03:37.516
Then that shall be done.

00:03:37.516 --> 00:03:38.640
They get their wishes here.

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:41.080
"Johnny Depp, Fate, and the
Double Decker Hollywood Tour

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:42.040
Bus."

00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:43.260
BJ NOVAK: That's a story--
some of these stories have--

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:44.020
TODD WOMACK: These are fiction.

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.353
BJ NOVAK: These are all fiction.

00:03:45.353 --> 00:03:47.495
I should have made
that more clear maybe.

00:03:47.495 --> 00:03:48.870
TODD WOMACK: It
says on the back.

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:49.800
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.730
That's one in which Johnny Depp
faces an existential crisis

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:56.225
while riding a motorcycle
alongside a Hollywood tour

00:03:56.225 --> 00:03:57.700
bus that recognizes him.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:03:59.270
And he feels more
and more compelled

00:03:59.270 --> 00:04:02.260
to show off for the tour bus.

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:07.260
And it goes to a real
extreme of fate and legacy.

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:08.944
And it ends, as
many of the stories

00:04:08.944 --> 00:04:10.610
do-- not many, as
several of the stories

00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:12.670
do-- with a discussion question.

00:04:12.670 --> 00:04:15.045
TODD WOMACK: Right, which you
have in the back, questions

00:04:15.045 --> 00:04:15.280
for discussions.

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:16.440
BJ NOVAK: I have more discussion
questions in the back.

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:17.570
TODD WOMACK: Yeah,
discussion questions.

00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:19.589
BJ NOVAK: Yeah, I figured
I'd just jump the gun

00:04:19.589 --> 00:04:22.160
and make the academic version
of the book for when it's

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:23.922
a classic taught in schools.

00:04:23.922 --> 00:04:25.380
I'd just save
everyone the trouble.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:26.130
TODD WOMACK: Yeah.

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:27.500
That'll go well in this crowd.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:30.790
"Wikipedia Brown and the
Case of the Missing Bicycle."

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:34.820
BJ NOVAK: Wikipedia
Brown is a detective.

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.090
A child detective.

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:38.040
He's not perfect.

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:39.060
He never said he was.

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:41.010
But he works fast,
and he works for free.

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:45.760
TODD WOMACK:
"Confucius at Home."

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:48.730
BJ NOVAK: "Confucius at Home"
is about the philosopher

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:53.570
Confucius, who has a scribe
with him at all times.

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:58.890
And everything that he says,
the scribe takes for wisdom.

00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:01.000
And sometimes, that
annoys Confucius.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.680
And sometimes, he thinks, well,
that does sound pretty good.

00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:05.414
That's another one
I'd be happy to read.

00:05:05.414 --> 00:05:06.330
It's a very short one.

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:07.370
TODD WOMACK: Great.

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:09.360
"Heyyyyy, Rabbits."

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:11.360
BJ NOVAK: "Heyyyyy,
Rabbits" is an abstract one.

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:12.100
TODD WOMACK: Did
I say that wrong?

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:12.920
BJ NOVAK: No, you
said it perfectly.

00:05:12.920 --> 00:05:13.520
I said it wrong.

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:15.103
TODD WOMACK: There's
five Ys in there.

00:05:15.103 --> 00:05:15.740
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:19.550
"Heyyyyy, Rabbits" is a
very abstract and short one

00:05:19.550 --> 00:05:24.020
about a man who-- sort of
a parable about commitment.

00:05:24.020 --> 00:05:28.800
A man who lives alone,
and sees a rabbit hopping

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:30.920
through his yard,
and wishes there

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:34.980
were a way to
attract many rabbits.

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:39.280
But he doesn't want to keep
them cooped up or trap them.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:41.650
He doesn't want any
commitment to the rabbits.

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:45.080
So he wonders how he can
just see more rabbits,

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:49.366
hang around with rabbits,
without having a rabbit.

00:05:49.366 --> 00:05:53.240
TODD WOMACK: Very allegorical--
today's young dating scene.

00:05:53.240 --> 00:05:55.137
This one, I really
like this one.

00:05:55.137 --> 00:05:57.470
" 'Everyone was Singing the
Same Song.' " Wait, quote, "

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:59.469
'Everyone was Singing the
Same Song,' end quote,

00:05:59.469 --> 00:06:02.110
the Duke of Earl Recalls
His Trip to America in June

00:06:02.110 --> 00:06:04.450
of 1962."

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:07.020
BJ NOVAK: Are people here
familiar with the song,

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:07.735
"Duke of Earl"?

00:06:07.735 --> 00:06:08.360
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:09.151
BJ NOVAK: OK, good.

00:06:09.151 --> 00:06:13.610
So I imagined that if there
were a real Duke of Earl who

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:17.120
visited America the year
that that song was a hit,

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:21.050
he would have had such
a beautiful experience.

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:24.550
And he might have
interpreted it as America

00:06:24.550 --> 00:06:27.970
being this place full
of harmony and life

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:30.720
where everyone is singing
the same song whenever

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:31.860
they meet him.

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:36.950
And to me, that was
probably an extreme version

00:06:36.950 --> 00:06:40.190
of how people remember
America right around then.

00:06:40.190 --> 00:06:43.850
In the early '60s, when we
idealized this America, when

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:45.610
despite all the things
under the surface,

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:48.870
it seemed as though everyone
was singing the same song.

00:06:48.870 --> 00:06:52.400
So that's his vision of America.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.740
TODD WOMACK: They will a capella
a song about you, about anyone.

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.231
BJ NOVAK: Yeah, but they
never sing his part.

00:06:58.231 --> 00:06:59.980
They're just kind of--
they can't help it.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:03.680
If you met the Duke of Earl,
you'd be like, [HUMMING]

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:05.570
Everyone kind of hums.

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:07.440
And they're all so
happy to see him.

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:09.910
They're like, you're
really the Duke of Earl?

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:12.230
They're just so excited.

00:07:12.230 --> 00:07:15.130
TODD WOMACK: So
I read that you--

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:18.520
these were the things that
you couldn't-- you had a bunch

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:21.490
of ideas in the writer's
room of "The Office"

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:27.200
that ended up as, not scraps,
but ideas that were different.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:30.910
Did you have a central storage
place for all this stuff or--

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:37.170
BJ NOVAK: Well, I kept a lot
of pocket notebooks maintaining

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:39.450
all these different
scraps, ideas.

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:42.019
And when "The Office"
ended, I thought that, well,

00:07:42.019 --> 00:07:43.560
time to look through
these notebooks.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:46.330
I probably have four
or five screenplays

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:47.830
if you add all these
ideas together.

00:07:47.830 --> 00:07:47.965
TODD WOMACK: Right.

00:07:47.965 --> 00:07:49.316
So you actually just
pen in everything.

00:07:49.316 --> 00:07:50.190
BJ NOVAK: Yeah, yeah.

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:53.455
Sometimes, I had them in my
phone, my Android device.

00:07:53.455 --> 00:07:55.080
TODD WOMACK: I saw
you before the show.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:55.460
BJ NOVAK: Am I doing well?

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:57.810
TODD WOMACK: You had
an iPhone, I think.

00:07:57.810 --> 00:07:59.640
BJ NOVAK: So I kept
them in my phone--

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.380
I don't remember what I was
using-- my phone, my notebooks.

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:05.760
And I thought, well, I'm sure
when "The Office" is over,

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:08.560
I've been writing
ideas for years.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:10.060
There must be some
movies in there.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:11.518
When I looked
through a bit, it was

00:08:11.518 --> 00:08:17.210
more like I had 800
opening shots and no movie.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:20.060
And so I started writing
them all out thinking,

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:22.330
well, let's see
what I have here.

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:24.660
And as I wrote them out,
many of them, I felt,

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:29.410
took their best
form as the story.

00:08:29.410 --> 00:08:32.390
Some of them became like
a "New Yorker" length

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:37.200
comedy piece or
piece of fiction.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.710
And others became
something you could really

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:41.809
fit even on Twitter or Tumblr.

00:08:41.809 --> 00:08:45.840
But all of them were
in their best form,

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:49.080
I felt, as my summary.

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.330
TODD WOMACK: In
writing the book, being

00:08:51.330 --> 00:08:54.980
a TV writer with a lot of
experience at this point,

00:08:54.980 --> 00:08:57.900
how would you
differentiate writing

00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:03.130
for TV purposefully as opposed
to writing stories for a book.

00:09:03.130 --> 00:09:06.010
BJ NOVAK: Well, I
was very focused on

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:07.720
how they could be similar.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:11.660
So for me, writing for an
audience was very important.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:14.580
And I read the stories out
loud, and actually booked

00:09:14.580 --> 00:09:17.670
a theater-- the UCB Theater
in LA-- and once a month,

00:09:17.670 --> 00:09:18.630
would read.

00:09:18.630 --> 00:09:20.680
I'd book a night
and read the stories

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:25.764
to a crowd of about 100 people,
and go up with a pen on stage,

00:09:25.764 --> 00:09:26.930
and edit in front of people.

00:09:26.930 --> 00:09:30.230
And that was my way of
keeping the work ethic

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:31.720
that I had from
television, where

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:35.320
I would write pages for the
cast, take them down to set,

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:38.020
think they were good,
and then figure out

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:41.080
if they were or not based on
how they played in front of me.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.370
Sometimes, I was even in
them, and I could literally

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:47.145
feel if I was scoring or not.

00:09:47.145 --> 00:09:48.520
And also, as a
stand up comedian,

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:50.714
I would write things,
think they were funny,

00:09:50.714 --> 00:09:51.880
and then take them on stage.

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:52.840
And sometimes, I was right.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:53.490
And sometimes, I was wrong.

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:55.180
But you never know
until you try it out.

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:57.790
So with these stories,
I tried to adapt that

00:09:57.790 --> 00:10:01.810
into a model of workshopping
that I'd seen David Sedaris do

00:10:01.810 --> 00:10:04.780
and tried to read
them and react live.

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:07.960
So I tried to make it like
TV in terms of my end goal

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:10.170
was always to entertain
and to connect.

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:12.474
So I would try to do that
viscerally and be honest with

00:10:12.474 --> 00:10:14.390
myself about what was
working and what wasn't.

00:10:17.117 --> 00:10:19.450
TODD WOMACK: That's sort of
like-- how did those go over

00:10:19.450 --> 00:10:21.360
as a show, do you think?

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:22.040
BJ NOVAK: Great.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:22.335
TODD WOMACK: Yeah?

00:10:22.335 --> 00:10:23.002
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:10:23.002 --> 00:10:25.460
TODD WOMACK: Did you-- because
it kind of sounds like you--

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:28.690
BJ NOVAK: I can see
your skepticism, yeah.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:31.314
See, I'm very attuned
to an audience.

00:10:31.314 --> 00:10:32.730
TODD WOMACK: I'm
just imagining it

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:35.740
as sort of like, hey, come on
and watch me work for an hour

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:36.480
down at the UCB.

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:37.517
How did you actually--

00:10:37.517 --> 00:10:39.850
BJ NOVAK: Well, I had done a
lot of shows as a stand up,

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:40.880
including at the UCB.

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:42.410
So I think people knew.

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:44.650
They weren't focused on
exactly what it would be.

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:45.590
They saw my name.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:47.090
They had seen me there before.

00:10:47.090 --> 00:10:49.680
It said I was doing, I called
it, "Uncollected Stories."

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:52.530
So they figured it
be something comedic.

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:55.530
It wasn't like I booked a
Broadway theater or something.

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:57.486
So by the time I
got there, I think

00:10:57.486 --> 00:11:00.110
you could see that I was wearing
my heart on my sleeve in terms

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:01.693
of how much I cared
about the stories.

00:11:01.693 --> 00:11:03.800
But the stories
are funny stories.

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:07.500
So I'm not a masochist.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:08.930
I read the stories
that I thought

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:11.040
would be most entertaining.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.220
So yeah.

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:14.700
But I'd seen Sedaris do
it so well that I really

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:18.380
wanted to make a live reading
an evening of entertainment,

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:20.487
and tell stories between
them, and really act out

00:11:20.487 --> 00:11:21.320
the different roles.

00:11:24.570 --> 00:11:27.950
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, so do you
have a favorite story or two

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:28.564
in the book?

00:11:28.564 --> 00:11:29.980
BJ NOVAK: They're
all my favorite.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:33.980
Oh god, I sound like
such a lame parent.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:36.286
I'm very relieved though,
because as I wrote the book,

00:11:36.286 --> 00:11:38.160
I was constantly swapping
stories in and out.

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:40.760
And I would change my mind at
the last minute about what was

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:41.635
good and what wasn't.

00:11:41.635 --> 00:11:44.960
So I was very happy, in the
end, that a year later, I really

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:45.754
do love each one.

00:11:45.754 --> 00:11:47.670
And I, inadvertently,
whenever anyone tells me

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.669
their favorite story, I
say, that's my favorite.

00:11:49.669 --> 00:11:51.590
And I mean it every time.

00:11:51.590 --> 00:11:54.870
Because as I wrote that story,
I was in the mindset of,

00:11:54.870 --> 00:11:58.460
this is my favorite thing
I've ever thought of.

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:01.050
If you don't do that, I
feel like you're not fully

00:12:01.050 --> 00:12:03.190
believing in your work.

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:05.860
TODD WOMACK: Going back a little
bit, I found out-- let's see.

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:07.360
You wrote for the
"Harvard Lampoon."

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:07.790
Is that right?

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:08.415
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:12:10.501 --> 00:12:12.500
TODD WOMACK: Can you tell
us what that was like?

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:14.260
Do we have some
Harvard grads in here?

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:14.760
One?

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:15.810
Just the one guy?

00:12:15.810 --> 00:12:16.657
Two people?

00:12:16.657 --> 00:12:17.740
Isn't this Google anymore?

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:19.820
What happened?

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:20.320
Over here?

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:21.770
Nobody?

00:12:21.770 --> 00:12:22.900
All right.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:23.650
Just three people?

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:24.560
BJ NOVAK: Eric
Schmidt's watching this.

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:26.130
He's like, we have a
Facebook problem again.

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:28.005
TODD WOMACK: Getting
killed by Schmidt, guys.

00:12:28.005 --> 00:12:29.530
Come on.

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:31.550
Yeah, tell us about that.

00:12:31.550 --> 00:12:35.030
Was that your first professional
writing sort of thing?

00:12:35.030 --> 00:12:37.710
BJ NOVAK: Well, that was
probably the first time

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:41.080
that I was held up to very
high standards for comedy.

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:43.530
So it's a real advantage.

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:47.405
I don't think there's that
much advantage to having been

00:12:47.405 --> 00:12:49.640
in the "Harvard Lampoon"
in terms of connections,

00:12:49.640 --> 00:12:51.900
which people really
think there is because so

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:53.090
many of its graduates go on.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:55.740
I think the real
advantages are twofold.

00:12:55.740 --> 00:12:59.490
One is that first of all,
you leave with the confidence

00:12:59.490 --> 00:13:01.120
that this could
be a real career.

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.860
I think many funny
people, most funny people,

00:13:04.860 --> 00:13:08.660
never really think that
they can be a comedy writer.

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:11.960
And even if they do
wonder about it sometimes,

00:13:11.960 --> 00:13:16.000
they certainly don't think
that after a year or two

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.060
of unemployment and failure in
trying to be a comedy writer.

00:13:19.060 --> 00:13:21.227
But a "Harvard Lampoon"
graduate has seen it happen.

00:13:21.227 --> 00:13:23.643
So they get out there, and
they write script after script,

00:13:23.643 --> 00:13:25.000
and meeting after meeting.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.970
And they're confident enough
to persevere to the point

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:29.460
where it actually
starts working.

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:31.650
So it's sort of a Dumbo's
feather in that way.

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:36.810
The other advantage is
that people are mercilessly

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:41.660
critiquing your comedy
at age 18, 19, 20.

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:43.580
And most people who
are just naturally

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:46.830
funny with their friends, their
friends never critique them.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:49.170
They're never like, that
story started out great.

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:52.110
Then I knew where
you were going.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:55.190
It ended strong, but I thought
the second to last joke

00:13:55.190 --> 00:13:58.400
felt kind of flat because it
was the same as the first joke.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:13:59.640
No friend ever says that.

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:01.420
So here, you're
actually, wow, you're

00:14:01.420 --> 00:14:03.390
held up to that
kind of standard.

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:05.450
And you get trained
a little bit.

00:14:05.450 --> 00:14:07.134
TODD WOMACK: Right on.

00:14:07.134 --> 00:14:09.745
A lot of SNL writers do
come out of there, right?

00:14:09.745 --> 00:14:10.370
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:12.120
TODD WOMACK: Like
a crazy proportion.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:12.900
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.117
I don't know about
the exact proportion,

00:14:15.117 --> 00:14:15.950
but I know a lot do.

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:17.586
TODD WOMACK: It's 54%, actually.

00:14:17.586 --> 00:14:18.012
BJ NOVAK: Oh, wow.

00:14:18.012 --> 00:14:18.864
TODD WOMACK: I'm just kidding.

00:14:18.864 --> 00:14:20.610
BJ NOVAK: You guys, everyone
on a laptop was like--

00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:21.985
TODD WOMACK: I
just made that up.

00:14:21.985 --> 00:14:23.300
I just made that up.

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:25.690
So take me through--
so you're writing

00:14:25.690 --> 00:14:27.300
for the "Harvard Lampoon."

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:29.500
You got on "The
Office" very quickly.

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.566
But you had a writing
credit before that, right?

00:14:31.566 --> 00:14:32.940
BJ NOVAK: I did
write for a show.

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:36.300
Does anyone remember a show on
the CW called-- actually, no.

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:37.290
Then, it was the WB.

00:14:37.290 --> 00:14:39.937
Does anyone remember a
show called, "Raising Dad?"

00:14:39.937 --> 00:14:41.130
AUDIENCE: [MURMURING]

00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:43.560
BJ NOVAK: Some embarrassed,
anonymous murmurs.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:45.102
Yeah, that's how I
feel about it too.

00:14:45.102 --> 00:14:46.851
Yeah, I might've seen
that a couple times.

00:14:46.851 --> 00:14:48.870
TODD WOMACK: That was a
polite murmur, I think.

00:14:48.870 --> 00:14:51.230
BJ NOVAK: It was a show
starring Bob Saget.

00:14:51.230 --> 00:14:51.640
TODD WOMACK: He's great.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:53.306
BJ NOVAK: And his two
teenage daughters,

00:14:53.306 --> 00:14:57.810
who now are quite successful--
Kat Dennings and Brie Larson,

00:14:57.810 --> 00:14:59.780
both of whom have
great acting careers.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:01.710
So I was 21.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:07.620
I had put up a show at
Harvard called the BJ Show.

00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:10.770
It was not-- yeah, anyway.

00:15:10.770 --> 00:15:13.260
And I had invited-- I
traded on the Harvard

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:14.260
name pretty shamelessly.

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:16.440
I wrote a letter
called, "To Bob Saget."

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:19.230
And I said, the
"Harvard Lampoon"

00:15:19.230 --> 00:15:21.620
would like to honor you,
give you some award.

00:15:21.620 --> 00:15:23.200
Basically, they
let me give anyone

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:24.680
an award if you're on staff.

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:26.380
Yeah, sure, give him an award.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:27.350
How much is a trophy?

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:30.000
I'll say you're Comedian of
the Century or something.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.420
And would you like to come
and receive your honor?

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:35.310
And also, there's
this show called

00:15:35.310 --> 00:15:37.070
the BJ Show, funny coincidence.

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:38.560
I'd love to have you in.

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:41.020
And so he was very
flattered and happy to have

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:42.350
Harvard on his resume.

00:15:42.350 --> 00:15:43.590
So he said sure.

00:15:43.590 --> 00:15:44.722
So he came out.

00:15:44.722 --> 00:15:46.430
And the show-- I put
a lot into the show.

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:47.471
The show was really good.

00:15:47.471 --> 00:15:51.400
We wrote a script called,
"The Lost Full House Episode,"

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:53.230
that I acted in with him.

00:15:53.230 --> 00:15:56.360
I played Uncle Jesse, and he
played-- he played himself.

00:15:56.360 --> 00:15:57.665
He played Danny Tanner.

00:15:57.665 --> 00:15:58.830
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, you've gotta
give yourself the Jesse part.

00:15:58.830 --> 00:16:00.496
BJ NOVAK: It was an
R-rated "Full House"

00:16:00.496 --> 00:16:05.720
episode in which Danny tries
to teach Michelle about sex.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:08.380
And then Uncle Jesse overhears
and realizes that Danny

00:16:08.380 --> 00:16:09.930
doesn't know what sex is.

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:13.560
And so then Uncle
Jesse explains sex

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:16.642
to Danny, who then becomes
a sex-crazed maniac.

00:16:19.317 --> 00:16:21.900
It didn't really make sense, I
guess, if you thought about it.

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:24.190
But it definitely
worked on stage.

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:26.890
So on the strength of
that, he and the creator

00:16:26.890 --> 00:16:29.820
of "Raising Dad"
offered to hire me

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:34.490
as the young writer who would
edge up their writer's room.

00:16:34.490 --> 00:16:36.170
And I was happy to do it.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:38.378
I wasn't looking for something
like that at the time,

00:16:38.378 --> 00:16:39.471
but I knew not to say no.

00:16:39.471 --> 00:16:40.970
So that became my
first writing job.

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:48.580
Then that was cancelled,
shockingly, after a year.

00:16:48.580 --> 00:16:52.390
And then after that, I had
some money saved up now,

00:16:52.390 --> 00:16:55.040
but I was back to square one.

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:56.830
And then I started
doing stand up comedy,

00:16:56.830 --> 00:16:59.210
and that eventually led to
"The Office" about two years

00:16:59.210 --> 00:16:59.610
after that.

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:02.109
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, I heard you
say that Greg Daniels saw you

00:17:02.109 --> 00:17:04.380
at the Ha Ha, which I've
done plenty of shows at.

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:06.050
I mean, it's a special place.

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:06.750
BJ NOVAK: Greg
Daniels, I'm sure,

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:07.880
has never been to the Ha Ha.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:08.250
TODD WOMACK: That's
what I was thinking.

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:08.660
I wanted to talk
to you about that.

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:10.170
BJ NOVAK: I started
at the Ha Ha.

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:10.900
He saw me at the Improv.

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:11.180
TODD WOMACK: OK.

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:11.750
Great, great.

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:12.150
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:13.380
Greg Daniels does
not go to the Ha Ha.

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:14.530
TODD WOMACK: That's what I
was going to actually ask you.

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:16.109
BJ NOVAK: That is the
world's saddest place.

00:17:16.109 --> 00:17:17.190
TODD WOMACK: I know for a fact.

00:17:17.190 --> 00:17:17.790
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:19.010
They should have
that under the sign.

00:17:19.010 --> 00:17:20.509
It would probably
get more business.

00:17:20.509 --> 00:17:23.839
Ha Ha Comedy Club-- the
World's Saddest Place.

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:26.589
People would be like, that's
an interesting juxtaposition.

00:17:26.589 --> 00:17:28.844
They have a sophisticated
sense of comedy over there.

00:17:28.844 --> 00:17:30.510
TODD WOMACK: But no,
it's quite literal.

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:30.930
BJ NOVAK: No, no.

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:32.263
It's the saddest place on earth.

00:17:32.263 --> 00:17:34.380
This is so you don't
sue us for expecting

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:35.644
a positive experience.

00:17:35.644 --> 00:17:37.060
TODD WOMACK: A lot
of comedy clubs

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:38.960
though, there's just not
a lot of joy in the--

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:40.810
BJ NOVAK: Not a lot of
joy in a comedy club.

00:17:40.810 --> 00:17:42.160
Yeah.

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:45.564
TODD WOMACK: But so Greg Daniels
sees you, and what happens?

00:17:45.564 --> 00:17:46.480
BJ NOVAK: Greg saw me.

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:48.438
I had been unemployed
now for a couple of years

00:17:48.438 --> 00:17:50.900
and had been doing stand
up just about every night,

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:54.655
and had built up now a
pretty good stand up act.

00:17:54.655 --> 00:17:57.880
A pretty good brief act,
like 10 minutes-- 10 minutes

00:17:57.880 --> 00:18:00.550
that was really good and about
20 that were not very good.

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:02.590
But on these
showcases, they have

00:18:02.590 --> 00:18:05.940
you do the seven that are good.

00:18:05.940 --> 00:18:09.070
So I was doing this
show, and Greg was there.

00:18:09.070 --> 00:18:12.254
And he was putting together the
cast for the very early stages

00:18:12.254 --> 00:18:12.920
of "The Office."

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:15.378
TODD WOMACK: So if you guys
don't know who Greg Daniels is,

00:18:15.378 --> 00:18:17.900
he's a big-time TV
producer, showrunner.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:20.130
And he was tasked
with Americanizing

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:21.180
the British "Office."

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:22.480
BJ NOVAK: He had been a
writer for "The Simpsons"

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:23.580
and "Saturday Night Live."

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:26.990
And then had created
"King of the Hill,"

00:18:26.990 --> 00:18:28.769
and now was looking
for his next thing.

00:18:28.769 --> 00:18:31.310
And "The Office," at that time,
was a very acclaimed but very

00:18:31.310 --> 00:18:32.860
short-lived British show.

00:18:32.860 --> 00:18:36.690
And the producers had
found him and asked him

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:38.549
if he would adapt
the American show.

00:18:38.549 --> 00:18:40.340
So he was the one in
charge of figuring out

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:41.310
what this would be.

00:18:41.310 --> 00:18:42.101
TODD WOMACK: Right.

00:18:42.101 --> 00:18:44.030
So did you have that,
"I like you, kid,"

00:18:44.030 --> 00:18:47.155
moment that so many
people yearn for?

00:18:47.155 --> 00:18:47.780
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:18:47.780 --> 00:18:50.060
That's not-- he
doesn't talk like that.

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:51.560
TODD WOMACK: He's
not from the '30s?

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:52.320
BJ NOVAK: No.

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:52.950
No.

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:55.440
This happened in this century.

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:57.280
But it was that same vibe.

00:18:57.280 --> 00:18:58.711
TODD WOMACK: Barely, though.

00:18:58.711 --> 00:18:59.960
Three years into this century.

00:18:59.960 --> 00:19:00.876
BJ NOVAK: That's true.

00:19:00.876 --> 00:19:02.590
Early into this
century, just barely.

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:04.560
Because in the '90s, we
all talked like that.

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:07.550
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, I remember.

00:19:07.550 --> 00:19:09.650
BJ NOVAK: I was there.

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:12.550
So yeah, he saw me and
asked for a meeting.

00:19:12.550 --> 00:19:16.680
And he saw me for
the role of The Temp,

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:18.650
as he called it,
someone who thought

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:20.496
he was better than this place.

00:19:20.496 --> 00:19:22.870
Quiet and thought he was better
than this place, which is

00:19:22.870 --> 00:19:24.920
sort of a vibe I had on stage.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:27.100
I think I wore a suit back then.

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:29.740
I had very good one-liners, and
I paused a lot between them.

00:19:29.740 --> 00:19:32.600
And I think that
was out of fear,

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:35.050
but I think people
interpreted that as cockiness.

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:36.550
TODD WOMACK: You're
just stretching.

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:37.650
You're just sweating
inside, stretching it.

00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:38.275
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:19:38.275 --> 00:19:42.030
And he knew that he
would like, ideally,

00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:43.960
to have writer-actors on shown.

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:45.800
And he knew that I
had written before.

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:47.650
So he talked to me
about potentially

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:48.970
being a writer-actor.

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:51.095
TODD WOMACK: To which you
replied, where do I sign?

00:19:51.095 --> 00:19:51.719
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:19:51.719 --> 00:19:52.620
Where do I sign?

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:53.411
TODD WOMACK: Great.

00:19:53.411 --> 00:19:55.320
And so that started very soon.

00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:57.890
You went on for
eight years, right?

00:19:57.890 --> 00:19:59.060
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:01.239
It was a nine-year
show, actually.

00:20:01.239 --> 00:20:02.280
I was on for eight years.

00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:04.630
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, right.

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:08.360
So I saw that you actually were
executive producing by the end,

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:09.780
directing, writing stories.

00:20:09.780 --> 00:20:11.530
BJ NOVAK: Well, executive
producing really

00:20:11.530 --> 00:20:16.070
means, in most
cases, that you have

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:18.000
been a writer for a long time.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.700
And my least favorite
thing, by the way,

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:25.530
is when people try to give you
metaphors so you'll understand.

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:27.932
Like, it's like for you guys
when-- I hate that so much.

00:20:27.932 --> 00:20:28.890
TODD WOMACK: Maybe not.

00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:29.320
They don't work in TV.

00:20:29.320 --> 00:20:31.819
BJ NOVAK: But it's like here
or in any other profession when

00:20:31.819 --> 00:20:34.550
you might get a job title
increase every year,

00:20:34.550 --> 00:20:37.277
but you've been doing the
same thing every year.

00:20:37.277 --> 00:20:38.860
You've just been
doing it well, so you

00:20:38.860 --> 00:20:39.970
keep getting a new title.

00:20:39.970 --> 00:20:42.150
That's what the writers
on any show tend to be.

00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:47.130
So I started as an
executive story editor,

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:51.570
that is really like-- did anyone
take swimming lessons in camp?

00:20:51.570 --> 00:20:54.490
And it's like beginner,
advanced beginner, intermediate,

00:20:54.490 --> 00:20:55.710
it's like those levels.

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:57.950
So the levels-- and I'll
go through them right now.

00:20:57.950 --> 00:21:02.015
They're official levels in
comedy writing on a Writers

00:21:02.015 --> 00:21:02.890
Guild sponsored show.

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:04.590
You start as a staff writer.

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:06.100
That's what I was
in "Raising Dad."

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:07.530
Then story editor.

00:21:07.530 --> 00:21:09.370
Then executive story editor.

00:21:09.370 --> 00:21:10.900
I'm not making this up.

00:21:10.900 --> 00:21:13.080
Then co-producer.

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:15.680
Then producer.

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:18.245
There could be many
producers though.

00:21:18.245 --> 00:21:20.540
And sometimes, there's only
one co-producer and several

00:21:20.540 --> 00:21:22.260
producers.

00:21:22.260 --> 00:21:24.080
I'm not making this up.

00:21:24.080 --> 00:21:24.919
Staff writer.

00:21:24.919 --> 00:21:25.460
Story editor.

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:26.480
Executive story editor.

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:27.260
Co-producer.

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:28.540
Producer.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:31.180
Supervising producer.

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:34.260
Co-executive producer.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:35.475
Executive producer.

00:21:35.475 --> 00:21:36.850
TODD WOMACK:
Congratulations, you

00:21:36.850 --> 00:21:37.540
made it all the way to the top.

00:21:37.540 --> 00:21:38.915
BJ NOVAK: It just
means I made it

00:21:38.915 --> 00:21:42.110
to the final level of
Scientology, basically.

00:21:42.110 --> 00:21:42.810
Yeah.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:43.772
I met L. Ron Hubbard.

00:21:43.772 --> 00:21:44.980
TODD WOMACK: Congratulations.

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:45.800
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:48.175
TODD WOMACK: I could feel it
in your hand when you shake.

00:21:48.175 --> 00:21:49.490
And there are two microphones.

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:50.684
If you all want to start.

00:21:50.684 --> 00:21:52.600
If anyone has questions,
go ahead and step up.

00:21:52.600 --> 00:21:55.320
And we'll grab you
when you come up.

00:21:55.320 --> 00:21:58.260
But feel free to also do that.

00:21:58.260 --> 00:22:02.385
Really quickly, so we we're
going to take some questions.

00:22:02.385 --> 00:22:03.010
BJ NOVAK: Sure.

00:22:03.010 --> 00:22:05.200
TODD WOMACK: You are going to
do a little signing afterward.

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:07.280
Would you like to read
some of the book now?

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:07.630
BJ NOVAK: Sure.

00:22:07.630 --> 00:22:09.588
TODD WOMACK: What story
would you like to read?

00:22:09.588 --> 00:22:12.550
BJ NOVAK: I can read maybe
the more internet age

00:22:12.550 --> 00:22:14.109
ones because we're here.

00:22:14.109 --> 00:22:15.400
TODD WOMACK: Whatever you want.

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:18.950
BJ NOVAK: I can read
"The Man Who Posted

00:22:18.950 --> 00:22:21.030
Pictures of Everything He Ate."

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:22.010
Very brief story.

