00:27:20.485 --> 00:27:23.150
Do you prefer heading
down this path

00:27:23.150 --> 00:27:25.110
of being a book
writer versus sticking

00:27:25.110 --> 00:27:27.542
with traditional
screen and TV writing?

00:27:27.542 --> 00:27:29.000
If you could call
that traditional.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:32.510
BJ NOVAK: Yeah, I think I
will be back next in what

00:27:32.510 --> 00:27:33.390
I was doing before.

00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:37.290
But I became a much
richer, I think,

00:27:37.290 --> 00:27:40.120
entertainer and writer
from doing this.

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:42.580
Where I could really
go deep into who I was

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:43.860
and what I wanted to say.

00:27:43.860 --> 00:27:46.370
And some of the other
stories are deeper than that.

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:48.932
You're like, well,
that's not that deep.

00:27:48.932 --> 00:27:51.380
I could really go
deeper into ideas

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:53.520
and then really take
full responsibility

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:55.150
for bringing them
to an audience,

00:27:55.150 --> 00:27:59.450
reading them out loud,
promoting them online, designing

00:27:59.450 --> 00:28:02.800
the covers-- which obviously, I
put a lot of design work into.

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:04.784
TODD WOMACK: This one too.

00:28:04.784 --> 00:28:06.450
BJ NOVAK: Which took
a surprising amount

00:28:06.450 --> 00:28:08.310
of design work actually.

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:10.390
Simplicity can be difficult.

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:13.130
But I think I'm
much richer for it.

00:28:13.130 --> 00:28:15.400
But I think probably
what I'll do

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:19.653
next is back on those fields,
because what my real love is

00:28:19.653 --> 00:28:23.080
is connecting through
entertainment.

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:25.020
Making someone's
favorite something

00:28:25.020 --> 00:28:27.230
is what I always say
is what I want to do.

00:28:27.230 --> 00:28:30.600
So you can make a lot of
people's favorite something

00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:34.710
more if you do it
for more people.

00:28:34.710 --> 00:28:37.940
I hope no one ever
quotes me on that.

00:28:37.940 --> 00:28:38.560
Really vague.

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:40.690
But you get what
I'm trying to say.

00:28:40.690 --> 00:28:42.380
TODD WOMACK: While we're on this
topic of this book, real quick.

00:28:42.380 --> 00:28:44.796
If you haven't seen this one,
"The Book with No Pictures,"

00:28:44.796 --> 00:28:45.550
it's a kids' book.

00:28:45.550 --> 00:28:47.640
And it's really fun.

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.100
There's a video
of you reading it

00:28:49.100 --> 00:28:52.250
to a bunch of kids,
which is quite cool.

00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:53.517
The kids love this book, yeah?

00:28:53.517 --> 00:28:55.350
BJ NOVAK: It's a very
big hit with the kids.

00:28:55.350 --> 00:28:57.610
TODD WOMACK: I've
heard this before.

00:28:57.610 --> 00:28:58.270
I don't know.

00:28:58.270 --> 00:28:59.010
Do you want to describe it?

00:28:59.010 --> 00:28:59.900
Maybe I don't want
to butcher it.

00:28:59.900 --> 00:29:00.524
BJ NOVAK: Sure.

00:29:00.524 --> 00:29:05.720
This is a book with no pictures.

00:29:05.720 --> 00:29:09.710
I'll start it out for you. "This
is a book with no pictures.

00:29:09.710 --> 00:29:11.460
It might seem like
no fun for someone

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:14.740
to read you a book
with no pictures.

00:29:14.740 --> 00:29:17.990
It probably seems
boring and serious.

00:29:17.990 --> 00:29:21.010
Except--" I know
the book by heart.

00:29:21.010 --> 00:29:23.050
"Here's how books work.

00:29:23.050 --> 00:29:25.510
Everything the words say,
the person reading the book

00:29:25.510 --> 00:29:27.320
has to say.

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:30.240
No matter what.

00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:31.380
That's the deal.

00:29:31.380 --> 00:29:32.730
That's the rule.

00:29:32.730 --> 00:29:37.560
So that means even if
the words say-- Blork.

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:38.235
Wait, what?

00:29:38.235 --> 00:29:39.970
That doesn't even mean anything.

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:40.470
Bluurf.

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:41.270
Wait a second.

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:41.890
What?

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:44.214
This isn't the kind of
book I wanted to read."

00:29:44.214 --> 00:29:45.630
So that's the
premise of the book.

00:29:45.630 --> 00:29:48.700
And then it makes you say
all kinds of silly things.

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:52.270
"Yes, I am a monkey."
"I'm a robot monkey."

00:29:52.270 --> 00:29:53.680
You have to praise the kid.

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:55.840
"Best kid ever."

00:29:55.840 --> 00:29:59.560
Eventually, they usually laugh
just at the sight of this page

00:29:59.560 --> 00:30:03.155
because they know what things
like this are going to lead to.

00:30:03.155 --> 00:30:05.130
They call that
the Mayhem Spread.

00:30:05.130 --> 00:30:07.665
So the idea is
that the parent has

00:30:07.665 --> 00:30:09.040
to be engaged in
this read aloud.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:12.000
But really, the
secret message is

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.210
that words have
this great power,

00:30:14.210 --> 00:30:16.350
and you can abuse this power.

00:30:16.350 --> 00:30:18.310
That's how you know
it's a cool power.

00:30:18.310 --> 00:30:18.940
TODD WOMACK: This is great.

00:30:18.940 --> 00:30:19.990
I love the concept for this.

00:30:19.990 --> 00:30:20.060
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:30:20.060 --> 00:30:21.768
TODD WOMACK: How'd
you come up with that?

00:30:21.768 --> 00:30:23.910
BJ NOVAK: Well, I was
reading-- my best friend,

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:28.669
Ches, from college had a
kid who was two at the time.

00:30:28.669 --> 00:30:29.960
And I would read lots of books.

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:32.260
And he would always come up
to me holding a book for me

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:33.039
to read.

00:30:33.039 --> 00:30:35.080
And at some point, I
thought, this is very funny.

00:30:35.080 --> 00:30:37.310
He doesn't realize
how much power he has.

00:30:37.310 --> 00:30:41.330
Because I'm used to being
a co-executive producer

00:30:41.330 --> 00:30:44.720
or higher, and now,
I'm just an actor who

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:47.264
has to say whatever
lines he hands me.

00:30:47.264 --> 00:30:48.180
That's what a book is.

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:49.380
It's a script.

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:51.269
When you're two and
handing it to an adult,

00:30:51.269 --> 00:30:53.560
you're handing them a script
that they have to perform.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:56.375
So I thought, well,
what's the funniest script

00:30:56.375 --> 00:30:57.890
that a kid could hand you?

00:30:57.890 --> 00:30:59.330
Well, it would be
things that they

00:30:59.330 --> 00:31:04.220
know what it's going to say,
but you act so bewildered by.

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:06.050
So that was the
original idea for it.

00:31:06.050 --> 00:31:07.190
TODD WOMACK: Yeah, it's
a good, fun, little game.

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:07.560
BJ NOVAK: Yeah.

00:31:07.560 --> 00:31:10.059
And I guess the lesson that I
learned well from "The Office"

00:31:10.059 --> 00:31:14.590
is that, if something
crazy happens,

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:16.600
the real laughter is
on the reaction shot.

00:31:16.600 --> 00:31:19.247
So that's why the parent has
all this dialog like, what?

00:31:19.247 --> 00:31:20.330
I didn't want to say that.

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:21.790
What kind of book is this?

00:31:21.790 --> 00:31:23.249
Excuse me?

00:31:23.249 --> 00:31:24.415
That's where the kid laughs.

00:31:24.415 --> 00:31:26.690
It's not when you say
the outrageous thing.

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:28.386
It's when you react
deadpan to it.

00:31:28.386 --> 00:31:30.052
So that's a lesson I
took from the show.

00:31:30.052 --> 00:31:30.454
TODD WOMACK: Yeah.

00:31:30.454 --> 00:31:30.856
It's a great, great book.

00:31:30.856 --> 00:31:32.230
How about a question?

00:31:32.230 --> 00:31:32.940
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:31:32.940 --> 00:31:33.930
Thanks for coming.

00:31:33.930 --> 00:31:36.280
I got "One More Thing"
right when it came out.

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:38.480
And it was one of those
books I couldn't put down.

00:31:38.480 --> 00:31:38.910
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:39.850
AUDIENCE: Very well crafted.

00:31:39.850 --> 00:31:40.880
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:43.210
AUDIENCE: And so I
loved the comedic parts.

00:31:43.210 --> 00:31:46.640
But there were also some that
took a turn for the profound.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:49.390
They could be read
almost as parables.

00:31:49.390 --> 00:31:54.850
And I was curious as to how
much influence the fabulist

00:31:54.850 --> 00:31:56.510
writers had over you?

00:31:56.510 --> 00:32:00.480
Such as Italo Calvino with his
book, "Numbers in the Dark,"

00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:03.180
and those types of
story collections.

00:32:03.180 --> 00:32:05.320
BJ NOVAK: I don't
know that book.

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:08.270
I was a literature
student in school,

00:32:08.270 --> 00:32:10.260
and read a lot of
magical realism,

00:32:10.260 --> 00:32:13.940
and was drawn, in my
free time, to stuff

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:18.470
by George Saunders, Richard
Brautigan, Philip K. Dick

00:32:18.470 --> 00:32:19.170
sometimes.

00:32:19.170 --> 00:32:22.800
People that are--
the last name is

00:32:22.800 --> 00:32:24.720
more cerebral in
terms of his concepts,

00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:26.730
but they were actually
very emotional too.

00:32:26.730 --> 00:32:29.770
So I was always really
drawn to fiction

00:32:29.770 --> 00:32:34.210
that captures something,
as David Foster

00:32:34.210 --> 00:32:35.350
Wallace liked to say.

00:32:35.350 --> 00:32:39.820
That really used the
abstract to express something

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:41.980
that couldn't be
expressed in another way.

00:32:41.980 --> 00:32:43.590
So I was very drawn to that.

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:46.070
And often, when I started
with these stories,

00:32:46.070 --> 00:32:49.830
each one started with an
idea that made me laugh.

00:32:49.830 --> 00:32:52.205
One of them, probably the most
emotional one in the book,

00:32:52.205 --> 00:32:53.500
is called "Sophia."

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:58.150
And it started as a very
silly idea I had written down.

00:32:58.150 --> 00:33:04.230
It said, "First AI to feel
love falls in love with man

00:33:04.230 --> 00:33:06.440
who doesn't want commitment."

00:33:06.440 --> 00:33:08.300
And then I wrote,
"Garry Shandling?"

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:12.425
I thought it's sort of like
his old-time style to do that.

00:33:12.425 --> 00:33:13.800
But the story I
ended up writing,

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:18.380
"Sophia," I put so much
of my own observations,

00:33:18.380 --> 00:33:22.810
and hypocrisies, and
heartbreaks into,

00:33:22.810 --> 00:33:25.060
that it evolved into
something more that way.

00:33:25.060 --> 00:33:28.480
I think that type of fiction
had always been in me.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:31.430
I wouldn't have dared
to attempt it head on.

00:33:31.430 --> 00:33:36.290
But I sort of
accidentally pursued it

00:33:36.290 --> 00:33:40.399
in the service of trying
to make a comedic story.

00:33:40.399 --> 00:33:41.940
That was also a
lesson that I learned

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:46.490
from "The Office" in that the
biggest comedic moments tend

00:33:46.490 --> 00:33:48.540
to come when you're
emotionally invested.

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:50.960
So if I didn't
have a good joke, I

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:54.030
would just go deeper into truth
as far as I could until a joke

00:33:54.030 --> 00:33:55.902
presented itself.

00:33:55.902 --> 00:33:56.610
Thanks very much.

00:33:56.610 --> 00:33:57.460
I'm really glad
you liked the book.

00:33:57.460 --> 00:33:58.620
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:00.320
TODD WOMACK: Copies
for sale over there.

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:01.962
How about a question?

00:34:01.962 --> 00:34:03.920
AUDIENCE: Hey, thanks so
much again for coming.

00:34:03.920 --> 00:34:06.920
And I think I also owe you a
thank you for "Boo Boo Butt"

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:08.716
being a favorite word
of my two-year old's.

00:34:08.716 --> 00:34:11.350
BJ NOVAK: Oh, great.

00:34:11.350 --> 00:34:13.550
AUDIENCE: So it's clear
to me from listening

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:15.550
to the way you talk
about your process

00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:17.510
and also just hearing
you read, that you really

00:34:17.510 --> 00:34:21.020
have specific intonations for
the way things should be read,

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:24.850
or how quickly, and the voice
level and all that stuff.

00:34:24.850 --> 00:34:27.770
So it's very interesting that
you ultimately put it in a book

00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:32.060
where the speaker or the
reader really makes decisions

00:34:32.060 --> 00:34:33.120
on what it sounds like.

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:35.370
So I was just wondering if
you could talk a little bit

00:34:35.370 --> 00:34:37.159
about that and
why you ultimately

00:34:37.159 --> 00:34:38.739
decided to go with
a book as opposed

00:34:38.739 --> 00:34:40.531
to maybe a YouTube video.

00:34:40.531 --> 00:34:41.989
BJ NOVAK: And you
mean specifically

00:34:41.989 --> 00:34:42.906
the kids' book, right?

00:34:42.906 --> 00:34:43.780
AUDIENCE: Either one.

00:34:43.780 --> 00:34:46.080
Even just listening to the
way you read-- I'm sorry.

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:48.280
I haven't read "One
More Time" yet.

00:34:48.280 --> 00:34:49.360
"One More Thing," sorry.

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:52.549
But you definitely
have a vision and a way

00:34:52.549 --> 00:34:53.820
of hearing it in your head.

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:57.880
BJ NOVAK: Well, what I
did was, with this book,

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:03.670
I think a lot of parents don't
feel they know how to be funny.

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:04.420
I hear that a lot.

00:35:04.420 --> 00:35:06.628
And they hear this is a
funny book, and they're like,

00:35:06.628 --> 00:35:08.050
I'm not funny though.

00:35:08.050 --> 00:35:10.890
And they are funny, but they
don't have the confidence,

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:12.348
or they don't know
how to be funny.

00:35:12.348 --> 00:35:15.280
So again, I thought of
this book as a script.

00:35:15.280 --> 00:35:18.820
And with the layout, it
was important to have

00:35:18.820 --> 00:35:22.110
it seem like stage directions.

00:35:22.110 --> 00:35:25.450
But I didn't want them to think
about it or feel intimidated.

00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:29.090
So for example, "And
now, I'm reading

00:35:29.090 --> 00:35:31.564
you this book with my monkey
mouth and my monkey voice.

00:35:31.564 --> 00:35:32.230
That's not true.

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:35.075
I'm not a monkey."

00:35:35.075 --> 00:35:36.700
I think you can tell
that this is meant

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:40.320
to be more colorful,
a little goofy,

00:35:40.320 --> 00:35:42.299
and this is meant to
be straight and small.

00:35:42.299 --> 00:35:43.840
But you don't have
to think about it.

00:35:43.840 --> 00:35:47.280
And then I timed the page turns
to exactly where I thought

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:48.609
the pauses would naturally go.

00:35:48.609 --> 00:35:50.400
I tried to make it
seamless so you wouldn't

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:52.760
have to think about it.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:55.980
That said, there's a
little song in there.

00:35:55.980 --> 00:36:00.420
And I was reading it for my
best friend's son, Bruce,

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:01.630
after it was done.

00:36:01.630 --> 00:36:04.390
And Ches, my friend,
warned me, "by the way,

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:07.186
we do the song
differently in our house."

00:36:07.186 --> 00:36:08.390
So that's great.

00:36:08.390 --> 00:36:10.230
I love people having
their own traditions

00:36:10.230 --> 00:36:13.090
and their own spin on it.

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:16.569
It's like when you write
a play, and actors do it

00:36:16.569 --> 00:36:17.860
in all types of different ways.

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:20.250
But you make it clear
from the stage directions,

00:36:20.250 --> 00:36:23.350
and the dynamics,
and the exclamation

00:36:23.350 --> 00:36:26.160
points-- a thousand
little choices

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:28.400
dictate what you are picturing.

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:30.743
But then it's exciting when
people do different things.

00:36:30.743 --> 00:36:32.993
AUDIENCE: Have you ever heard
someone read it in a way

00:36:32.993 --> 00:36:34.270
that you were like, oh, no.

00:36:34.270 --> 00:36:35.193
That's not right.

00:36:35.193 --> 00:36:35.960
TODD WOMACK: Cut.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:36.570
BJ NOVAK: No.

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:39.420
But I've seen people do it.

00:36:39.420 --> 00:36:42.350
I've stolen from other
people, the way they read it.

00:36:45.500 --> 00:36:50.430
My cousin's husband reads it to
their kid in a very deadpan way

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:52.650
that I hadn't thought
of until I saw

00:36:52.650 --> 00:36:54.670
him do it and got huge laughs.

00:36:54.670 --> 00:36:57.310
Because I thought you try
to be a little animated.

00:36:57.310 --> 00:36:59.670
I'm not that animated
an actor, but I try

00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:01.440
to amp it up for a kids' book.

00:37:01.440 --> 00:37:03.639
But then he took it
get even further down.

00:37:03.639 --> 00:37:05.180
And it was funny
because the contrast

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:07.020
of the dignity of,
"I didn't want to say

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:09.580
that," that cracked the kid up.

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:11.357
So yeah, I'm always learning.

00:37:11.357 --> 00:37:12.190
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:12.190 --> 00:37:13.270
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:37:13.270 --> 00:37:15.169
TODD WOMACK: Let's
do another one.

00:37:15.169 --> 00:37:15.710
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:15.710 --> 00:37:18.200
You talked a little bit
about hoping that you make

00:37:18.200 --> 00:37:19.450
somebody's favorite something.

00:37:19.450 --> 00:37:21.700
And you definitely made one
of my favorite somethings,

00:37:21.700 --> 00:37:22.670
which is "The Office."

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:23.400
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:24.670
AUDIENCE: And this is a
pretty simple question,

00:37:24.670 --> 00:37:27.290
but I would actually love to
know what your favorite episode

00:37:27.290 --> 00:37:29.930
was in terms of either writing
or the way it panned out,

00:37:29.930 --> 00:37:33.650
and how you felt
about playing Ryan.

00:37:33.650 --> 00:37:34.650
BJ NOVAK: Thank you.

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:37.510
I'm somewhat-- like
the book of stories,

00:37:37.510 --> 00:37:39.760
I'll ask you at the end what
your favorite episode is,

00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:42.240
and I bet, instinctively,
I'll say, that's my favorite.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:45.460
Because I'm taken back to
the moment when it was all

00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:47.390
I thought about.

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:49.729
I would say, sort of
all-time, the one that

00:37:49.729 --> 00:37:52.270
makes me smile the most, if I
was about to die and they said,

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:54.269
we're going to play one
"Office" episode for you

00:37:54.269 --> 00:37:57.040
for old-time's sake, I'd
say, play "The Injury."

00:37:57.040 --> 00:37:57.765
That was the one.

00:37:57.765 --> 00:37:58.640
Mindy wrote that one.

00:37:58.640 --> 00:37:59.639
It made me really happy.

00:38:03.872 --> 00:38:06.080
It's opening monologue could
only have been our show.

00:38:06.080 --> 00:38:12.170
It was Steve Carell grilled his
foot on a George Foreman Grill

00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:15.730
because he liked to wake up to
the smell of crackling bacon.

00:38:15.730 --> 00:38:18.860
So he kept a Foreman
Grill next to his bed.

00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:20.210
And then he goes back to sleep.

00:38:20.210 --> 00:38:23.390
He has like a snooze button
system where he closes it,

00:38:23.390 --> 00:38:24.680
grills a little more.

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:27.465
Then he stepped on the
grill and punctuates it

00:38:27.465 --> 00:38:29.810
by showing the grill
marks on his foot.

00:38:29.810 --> 00:38:32.067
Then he thinks he's
handicapped, and comes in

00:38:32.067 --> 00:38:33.900
and lectures everyone
on handicap awareness.

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:40.450
Only Steve Carell could do that
without you turning off the TV,

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:43.140
saying this show is
fucking ridiculous.

00:38:43.140 --> 00:38:45.550
Because it was ridiculous,
but he grounded it

00:38:45.550 --> 00:38:51.250
with so much passion and
belief that you were like,

00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:54.589
I guess some people have to
work at a place like this.

00:38:54.589 --> 00:38:55.630
And it just became funny.

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:57.970
I think that one is a
great example of the show.

00:38:57.970 --> 00:39:00.470
It could have only been us, and
so it makes me really proud.

00:39:00.470 --> 00:39:01.678
What's your favorite episode?

00:39:01.678 --> 00:39:03.610
AUDIENCE: My favorite's
"Women's Appreciation"

00:39:03.610 --> 00:39:05.240
when there's the flasher
in the beginning.

00:39:05.240 --> 00:39:05.948
BJ NOVAK: Oh, OK.

00:39:05.948 --> 00:39:07.870
AUDIENCE: That's
one of my favorites.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:08.550
TODD WOMACK: "That's
my favorite too."

00:39:08.550 --> 00:39:08.940
That's your line.

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:09.810
BJ NOVAK: I didn't
work on that one.

00:39:09.810 --> 00:39:10.520
Yeah.

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:11.390
I didn't work on
that one that much.

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:12.170
AUDIENCE: Also "WUPHF."

00:39:12.170 --> 00:39:13.128
I think that's amazing.

00:39:13.128 --> 00:39:15.660
BJ NOVAK: Thank you. "WUPHF,"
I like that one a lot too.

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:17.410
I have a friend at
Google in Mountain View

00:39:17.410 --> 00:39:19.370
that says that
sometimes, ideas come up,

00:39:19.370 --> 00:39:20.900
and they compare
them to WUPFH.com.

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:24.984
So I'm honored to make
it into your lexicon.

00:39:24.984 --> 00:39:26.360
TODD WOMACK: Go ahead.

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:28.930
AUDIENCE: So when
you're writing a book,

00:39:28.930 --> 00:39:30.860
I guess it's more of
a solitary process.

00:39:30.860 --> 00:39:33.930
You're not necessarily writing
with other writers in a writing

00:39:33.930 --> 00:39:34.430
room.

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:37.907
You're not necessarily
writing for any actors.

00:39:37.907 --> 00:39:39.240
Do you find it more challenging?

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:42.430
Or what differences do
you find in that process?

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:44.890
BJ NOVAK: In some ways,
it's much more challenging.

00:39:44.890 --> 00:39:47.424
In some ways, it's
much-- I would

00:39:47.424 --> 00:39:49.340
change the word "challenging"
to "frustrating"

00:39:49.340 --> 00:39:50.554
as a better way to get at it.

00:39:50.554 --> 00:39:52.220
In some ways, it's
much more frustrating

00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:56.820
because when you hit a wall,
there's no coasting on a wave.

00:39:56.820 --> 00:39:59.140
It's sort of like--
well, I was going

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:01.390
to compare it to [INAUDIBLE],
but I don't know enough.

00:40:01.390 --> 00:40:03.342
But anyway, take that back.

00:40:03.342 --> 00:40:05.550
When you're in a writer's
room, there's so many ideas

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:08.510
going all the time
and so many minds

00:40:08.510 --> 00:40:11.180
going all the time,
that if you're stuck,

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:14.346
someone else is
going in a direction.

00:40:14.346 --> 00:40:15.470
It could be their own idea.

00:40:15.470 --> 00:40:18.050
It could be elaborating
on what you pitched.

00:40:18.050 --> 00:40:19.260
You can zone out.

00:40:19.260 --> 00:40:20.990
You can have a bad day.

00:40:20.990 --> 00:40:21.970
Be in a bad mood.

00:40:21.970 --> 00:40:25.010
Not have had enough coffee.

00:40:25.010 --> 00:40:27.677
Be mentally stuck
on a certain idea.

00:40:27.677 --> 00:40:29.510
And there's just all
these smart people that

00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:30.800
are just moving it forward.

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:33.550
And you can coast on
what they're doing.

00:40:33.550 --> 00:40:36.800
Or you can just be
leaning back, zoning out,

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:39.800
and then you have an-- someone
says something, you riff on it,

00:40:39.800 --> 00:40:41.030
and you save the day.

00:40:41.030 --> 00:40:43.490
And you weren't
stressed in the least.

00:40:43.490 --> 00:40:46.470
So that form of
collaboration is incredible.

00:40:46.470 --> 00:40:51.910
And it's very frustrating not to
have when you're working solo.

00:40:51.910 --> 00:40:54.160
But the frustration that you
avoid when you work solo,

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:59.950
I found, is that you get to be
your own harshest critic, which

00:40:59.950 --> 00:41:01.010
can be very liberating.

00:41:01.010 --> 00:41:04.720
Because when you make a pass
at yourself, you're there.

00:41:04.720 --> 00:41:09.070
So often, I would have an idea
that I loved on "The Office"

00:41:09.070 --> 00:41:11.360
or I had written a
script that I loved,

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:14.890
and they didn't want to cast
it the way I envisioned it.

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:18.110
Or they did and now
we're editing it,

00:41:18.110 --> 00:41:19.760
and they took out
the scene that was

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:22.030
the whole reason I wrote
the script because it

00:41:22.030 --> 00:41:23.590
didn't fit for time.

00:41:23.590 --> 00:41:26.820
And I was like, cut the rest
of the episode for time.

00:41:26.820 --> 00:41:28.700
That's the best scene
we've ever done.

00:41:28.700 --> 00:41:32.530
So those are so heartbreaking
as a writer and so frustrating.

00:41:32.530 --> 00:41:34.220
And you also lose
so much energy.

00:41:34.220 --> 00:41:36.011
And then sometimes,
you lose so much energy

00:41:36.011 --> 00:41:37.160
arguing for something.

00:41:37.160 --> 00:41:38.070
And you win.

00:41:38.070 --> 00:41:39.410
And then you were wrong.

00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:40.340
That happens too.

00:41:40.340 --> 00:41:41.890
Then that scene is just dead.

00:41:41.890 --> 00:41:45.004
So it's different
frustrations, I guess.

00:41:45.004 --> 00:41:46.170
You trade one for the other.

00:41:46.170 --> 00:41:48.628
And I think that's probably
why I would like to always keep

00:41:48.628 --> 00:41:50.280
going back and forth.

00:41:50.280 --> 00:41:50.780
Thanks.

00:41:50.780 --> 00:41:51.163
TODD WOMACK: Right on.

